Reasoning: The paper deals with the spread of genetic and cultural mutations on structured populations, which involves concepts from graph theory and network science. The modified Moran process on graphs is a stochastic process, which falls under the category of Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM). The study of the fixation probability and strong amplifiers involves game-theoretic and probabilistic arguments, which are relevant to the subfield of Game Theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the effects of graph structure on the spread of mutations, which is a topic of interest in Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Network Science (cs.NE). Finally, the paper proposes a positive result that applies to families of undirected graphs, which can be seen as a control problem in Systems and Control (cs.SY).
